<FIRST>r a AM-BusFatal 1stLd-Writethru a0701 08-06 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Fatal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Slams Into Tour Bus On Maine Coast Highway; Four Killed, 20 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with report that car driver had
had license suspended. Picks up 6th graf, `Eighteen bus...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of a car that slammed into a
tour bus, killing himself and three others, had just regained his
license the previous day after a suspension for driving to
endanger, police said Sunday.
   Kenneth Prior, 18, of Cushing also had lost his license on other
occasions for speeding and passing a stopped school bus, Department
of Public Safety spokesman Stephen McCausland said.
   State police investigating the accident Sunday said they didn't
know yet what caused the accident on coastal U.S. Route 1 Saturday
afternoon. Prior's car crossed the center line and hit a Travel
Tours of Oklahoma bus taking 47 people to Newfoundland. All of the
dead were people in the car. Twenty others were injured.
   ``One of the few witnesses to the accident indicated that the
car veered into the northbound lane for 30 to 40 yards and did not
attempt to take evasive action,'' spokesman Stephen McCausland of
the Maine Public Safety Department said Sunday. The witness was a
passenger on the bus, he said.
   ``If it hadn't been for that bus driver, there would have been
more killed,'' said a witness, Dorothy Kidney, manager of the
nearby Loon's Cry Campgrounds. ``I don't know how he kept that bus
from tipping over.''
   Also among the dead were Prior's fiancee, Marilyn McDougal, 17,
of Warren, who was seven months pregnant; her 8-year-old brother,
Adam McDougal of Warren; and Donald Grant, 18, of Thomaston.
   Eighteen bus passengers were treated and released at Penobscot
Bay Medical Center in Rockport. Right after the first crash,
another car slammed into the wreckage when it was unable to swerve
out of the way, injuring two other people.
   Witnesses said that the first car burst into flames and that
people from the campground ran and pulled the McDougal boy out and
then used a fire extinguisher to douse the fire. The boy died later
at a hospital, while the other three victims died at the scene.
   A bus passenger, Clinton Riggs of Tulsa, Okla., also applauded
the bus driver, Kevin Finnigan, for doing ``a beautiful job, a real
professional job'' in controlling the bus. And he expressed
gratitude to citizens who rushed to help.
   ``There were some real good people there helping real fast,''
Riggs said. ``We tend to think of Easterners as being a little bit
selfish and cold-hearted, but we were really impressed.''
   Emmy Stidham, tour guide for Travel Tours of Oklahoma, said the
passengers were from Oklahoma and Kansas and were en route to
Bangor for the night before continuing on to Newfoundland.
</TEXT>
