<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica 2dLd-Writethru a0779 08-06 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, 2d Ld-Writethru, a0779,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias: Leaders Will Set Timetable to Disband Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Talks end for day without agreement, new info-changes to conform
grafs 1-22. Pickup 18th graf: ``We look at it...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TELA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American presidents failed to
agree on a timetable for dismantling U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels
as the chief executives ended on Sunday night the second day of
their three-day summit.
   ``There is no accord about a timetable, but there is agreement
on mechanisms,'' Honduran President Jose Azcona told a news
conference after the second round of talks.
   The five presidents agreed at a meeting last February in El
Salvador to dismantle the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, but
postponed until this summit the ways to accomplish the task.
   The Bush administration wants to have the Contras, most of whom
are based in Honduras, remain intact until elections in Nicaragua
next February.
   Azcona said the U.S. government supplied documents to the
conference but has not tried to influence events.
   ``There was no pressure,'' he said.
   The U.S. government is not participating in the talks but sent
observers to the summit of the Presidents of Honduras, Nicaragua,
Guatemala, El Salvador and Costa Rica.
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias had been optimistic earlier
Sunday on an agreement dealing with the Contras, estimated to have
about 11,000 fighters.
   ``Today we'll reach an agreement, by consensus or from
exhaustion,'' he told The Associated Press.
   The timetable for dismantling the Contras is the major issue at
the conference.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega told reporters he is flexible
about the timetable and said he expected the resettlement to be
gradual.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani said he hoped the peace
talks also will deal with the nine-year-old guerrilla war in El
Salvador.
   Ortega bolstered his position by signing an agreement Friday
with his domestic political opposition that calls for demobilizing
the rebels. In exchange, he pledged democratic reforms.
   ``We have made advances, we have achieved substantial points, we
have exchanged opinions,'' Ortega told reporters after running on
the beach in this tiny Caribbean port town.
   None of the presidents interviewed before Sunday's session would
give details of the talks in Tula, about 200 miles north of
Tegucigalpa, the capital.
   But they would speak of their aspirations.
   ``I've seen a willingness to go forward with the (peace)
process,'' said Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo. ``There are
difficulties and we could stumble, but I hope we can move forward.''
   Arias, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for drafting a 1987 Central
American peace accord and promoting regional dialogue said:
   ``The positions of the presidents seem to me very frank and
sincere.
   ``The world is expecting much from us, principally the 28
million Central Americans who don't want war. Not to advance would
be to betray those hopes.''
   On Saturday, Ortega presented a letter from the Salvadoran
rebels asking the summit to promote negotiations with the
government on the Salvadoran conflict.
   ``We look at it positively,'' Cristiani said of the message.
``They must contact us directly and we can look at how to begin a
dialogue.''
   Cristiani said his only condition for negotiations was that
``once the talks begin, the rebels not look for excuses to break
them.''
   Before the summit ends Monday leaders also hope to agree on a
plan that would allow U.N. observer forces to monitor the
Honduras-Nicaragua and Honduras-El Salvador borders.
   The Contras have been fighting the Sandinistas since 1981. They
allege the Nicarguan government betrayed the revolution that ousted
late President Anastasio Somoza in 1979, ending 42 years of rule by
his family.
   Fighting has declined to sporadic clashes since last year, when
the two sides signed a temporary truce and the United States halted
military aid to the rebels. The United States still provides the
Contras with humanitarian aid.
   Talks aimed at a permanent end to the 7-year-old war, which has
left 50,000 dead, stand at an impasse.
</TEXT>
