<FIRST>r a PM-BumblingRobbers     08-06 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bumbling Robbers,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robbers ALmost Mess Up Their own Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bumbling bank robbers nearly foiled
their own getaway when they drove a stolen car over nails they had
strewn on the pavement to slow their pursuers.
   The car, with a flattened tire, was found less than two blocks
away from the Mercantile Bank branch the men robbed Friday.
Witnesses said they saw the men hustle out of the car and run
across a weed-covered field with the bank's money after abandoning
the vehicle at a car wash.
   The men wore ski masks and dark blue jumpsuits when they entered
the bank, took an undetermined amount of money from teller drawers
and a cash machine and told the bank's employees to lie on the
floor.
   As they left, they padlocked a thick chain they had wrapped
around the handles of the bank's front doors, apparently to slow
any possible pursuers, but left untouched an open rear door, said
Detective Les Ramsey.
   As the robbers pulled out of the parking lot, they tossed out
several boards studded with nails, their points protruding upward
to flatten the tires of any pursuing vehicles.
   They then drove over one of the boards, Ramsey said.
</TEXT>
