<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-EPA     08-06 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-EPA,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Chief Encouraged by Use of Fertilizer to Speed Oil Breakdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Applying fertilizer to help nature
decompose oil from the Exxon spill is the most encouraging
development so far in the response to the disaster, U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William Reilly said
Saturday.
   ``It's good news, and there hasn't been a lot where these oil
spills are concerned,'' Reilly said at a news conference.
   He said that by the time this season's beach cleanup ends in
mid-September, about 70 miles of shoreline will have been treated
with the available 500 metric tons of fertilizer. Oil has
contaminated nearly 800 miles of shoreline, according to the Coast
Guard.
   More of the French-made fertilizer will be manufactured by
spring, and there appears to be no limit on its use in future
cleanup of crude oil from the Exxon Valdez, Reilly said. The tanker
struck a reef in Prince William Sound on March 24, spilling nearly
11 million gallons of oil.
   Reilly, who on Friday inspected areas where EPA has tested the
fertilizer, said it was not clear how well the fertilizer will work
on aged oil.
   He said the EPA is committed to working on the cleanup until
restoration of affected areas is complete, and that he believes the
same is true of Exxon Corp.
   The oil company said last month that it expected to wrap up its
work in mid-September because of changing weather, and would
re-evaluate spill-affected areas next year to decide whether there
should be more work.
   Faced with charges by the state and others that the company was
reneging on an earlier promise to do whatever was necessary to
restore contaminated areas, company officials later said Exxon
would pursue beach cleanup in 1990 if directed by the Coast Guard.
Exxon Co. USA President W.D. Stevens told a congressional
subcommittee last week that the company would go along with any
``reasonable request.''
   State officials have been pressing for work over the winter as
weather permits, and for an unequivocal statement from Exxon that
it will be back in 1990 for more work that will satisfy state
standards.
   Exxon has an obligation and has made a commitment ``to stay the
course,'' Reilly said. But he added he is prepared to put pressure
on the company if work ends before restoration is complete.
   Restoration amounts to ``returning the sound as substantially as
possible to the condition that prevailed before the spill,'' Reilly
said. ``Obviously, in some areas that's going to be difficult to
achieve.''
   About $5 million has been spent on the fertilizer program, with
much of the money going for research. Exxon covered most of the
cost, and EPA expects the company to reimburse the agency for its
$1.6 million outlay, Reilly said.
   The treatment increases the number of microbes already eating
away at the oil. Reilly said the fertilizer can cut the time it
takes for oil to decompose from five to 10 years to three to five
years.
   ``What we have tried to do is speed nature up,'' Reilly said.
   The fertilizer method has not been used previously on Alaska
crude oil, nor has it been used on a large scale.
   Coast Guard Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, the federal on-scene
coordinator of the spill cleanup, authorized Exxon a week ago to
use fertilizer on heavily fouled shorelines.
</TEXT>
