<FIRST>u i AM-HurricaneDean 4thLd-Writethru a0611 08-06 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hurricane Dean, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0611,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Watch Posted for Bermuda</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE position.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hurricane warning was posted Saturday for Bermuda
as Hurricane Dean churned north with 85 mph winds on a path heading
for the Atlantic Ocean island, forecasters said.
   At midnight EDT, Dean's center was located near 29.0 north
latitude and 64.5 west longitude, or 235 miles south of Bermuda.
   Little change in strength was expected, said forecasters at the
National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables.
   Dean was pushing north at 21 mph, and was expected to keep the
same heading for the next 24 hours, putting the center near Bermuda
on Sunday morning.
   Winds were expected to hit 50 mph in Bermuda, with gusts to 60
mph, on Sunday afternoon, Bermuda television said. Tides of 3 to 5
feet above normal were considered possible.
   The storm could easily miss Bermuda because of its small size,
but forecasters said they wanted to alert the island's 65,000
residents to the possibility of hurricane conditions.
   A hurricane watch was upgraded later in the day to a hurricane
warning.
   Planes from the U.S. Naval Air Station on the island flew toward
the storm.
   Stores and businesses in Bermuda have been closed since Thursday
for a four-day holiday that revolves around the island's
championship cricket match.
   The hurricane's strongest winds are limited to a small area near
the center, but tropical-storm force winds of 39 mph extend 125
miles east of the center and 50 miles to the west.
   Dean, the second hurricane of the Atlantic season, became a
tropical storm Monday night, passed the hurricane threshold of 74
mph winds Tuesday and threatened the northern Caribbean islands
before shifting north late in the week.
</TEXT>
