<HEAD>Iran Press Says More Anti-U.S. and Israel Strikes by Lebanon groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's kidnapping of a Lebanese Shiite
Moslem cleric has strengthened the belief of Lebanese Moslem groups
that they must strike against Israel and its supporters, an Iranian
daily said Sunday.
   Jomhori Islami, quoted by Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency,
referred to the abduction of Sheik Abdul-Karin Obeid by Israeli
commandos July 28.
   ``If any group questioned the infliction of blows on Israel and
the United States before the Zionist abduction of Jibchit's Friday
prayer leader (Obeid), they are now resolute in their decision that
there is no alternative but to inflict heavy blows on Zionist
occupiers and their supporters,'' the newspaper said.
   It welcomed U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's
call for the release of all hostages held in Lebanon, according to
IRNA, monitored in Nicosia.
   But the newspaper criticized Perez de Cuellar for making the
suggestion only after the killing of American hostage Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins. The Marine's pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
abuductors said they hanged him Monday in retaliation for Obeid's
abduction.
   ``Why did he not ask for the release of all hostages earlier?
When the execution of another American became serious he
immediately thought about a solution,'' Jomhuri Islami said of
Perez de Cuellar.
   This reference was to U.S. hostage Joseph James Cicippio, 58,
who is being held by the Revolutionary Justice Organization,
another group of pro-Iranian Lebanese Shiites. The group gave him a
reprieve on Thursday and made a proposal for teh release of
Lebanese and Palestinian prisoners in Israel.
   IRNA quoted the daily Abrar as echoing the words of Iranian
President Hashemi Rafsanjani in saying that ``the Lebanese issue
and the hostage crisis have rational solutions provided the United
States and the West see the realities in the world.''
   Abrar said the United States and Israel conspired in the
kidnapping of Obeid.
   IRNA quoted the newspaper Kayhan International as saying that
Higgins and those facing a similar fate were victims of the
mistaken policies of the United States and Britain.
   ``If the United States and Britain did not support the terrorist
Israeli government ... the course of events would not be the way
they are today. Today they are reaping what they planted
yesterday,'' the paper said.
