<FIRST>u i BC-Dean     08-06 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dean,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Dean On Way To Bermuda</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0649 to restore AP logo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER SCOTTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents taped up their windows and
stocked up on emergency supplies as Hurricane Dean swept north
toward the island Sunday, packing maximum sustained winds of 90 mph
and occasional gusts of 100 mph.
   The National Weather Service in Miami said that at 9 a.m. EDT,
Dean's center was located near 30.5 north latitude and 64.8 west
longitude, or 125 miles south of Bermuda.
   Air force reconnaissance reports indicated Dean was
strengthening while moving on a course just west of due north. On
that course the center was due to pass over or just to the west of
Bermuda near noon EDT, the weather service said.
   Rainfall of 3 to 5 inches was expected to accompany the
hurricane.
   Bermuda residents, some still celebrating an annual four-day
holiday weekend, were urged on Saturday to secure their homes,
making sure shutters were in good order and checking on stocks and
emergency supplies. On Sunday many windows of homes were already
taped up.
   Shops on Saturday did a roaring trade in candles and flashlights
as residents recalled the power cuts of Sept. 1987 after Hurricane
Emily rampaged across the 21-square-mile island, home to about
65,000 people.
   Sgt. John Instone, a spokesman for the Bermuda government's
emergency services, said Sunday that authorities were on ``bravo
alert'' _ the second of a three-stage series measuring weather
conditions.
   Lt. Caron Rupre at the U.S. Naval Air Station in Bermuda said
Dean was expected to pass Bermuda 25 miles to the southwest. But
she added: ``With Dean, there's potential for hurricane-force winds
of a much longer duration than Emily.''
</TEXT>
