<HEAD>Four Dead, 68 Hurt in Pakistani Blasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb hidden in a potato crate
exploded Sunday at a vegetable market in this frontier city,
killing four people and wounding 31, police said. In another city,
37 people were reported injured in two blasts.
   No one claimed responsibility for any of the bombs. In the past,
authorities have blamed such attacks on the Marxist government of
Afghanistan.
   Pakistan provides headquarters to the most powerful guerrilla
forces fighting to overthrow the Afghan government. Afghanistan
also claims that Pakistani forces are fighting with the guerrillas,
but Pakistan denies the claim.
   The bomb in the market went off shortly after dawn, authorities
said.
   The wounded included nine Afghan refugees, hospital officials
said.
   Most of the estimated 3 million Afghan war refugees in Pakistan
are housed in tent villages surrounding Peshawar, which is near the
Afghan border.
   In Rawalpindi 120 miles to the east, 37 people were injured when
two bombs about a mile apart ripped through a crowded area,
hospital sources said.
   The bombs, which were hidden in taxis, went off in midafternoon
within minutes of each other.
   One witness, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he saw
four people get out of one of the taxis 15 minutes before it
exploded.
   The explosions shattered windows in nearby buildings and
destroyed eight vehicles, witnesses said.
   Scores of shoppers fled in panic.
   ``There was a big blast, and people started running everywhere
trying to find a place to hide,'' said Abdul Salam. He was in a
hospital for treatment of facial cuts from flying shrapnel.
