<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Strikes     08-06 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Return After Strike in Soviet Vorkuta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners who walked off their jobs to protest a
lack of information about government concessions returned to work
Sunday, the Tass news agency reported.
   The official news agency said all mines and associated coal
facilities of the Arctic Vorkuta region resumed work at midnight.
   Miners in 11 of the Pechora Coal Basin's 13 mines about 1,100
miles northeast of Moscow walked off their jobs Saturday in a
renewal of the labor unrest that wracked the Soviet Union last
month.
   The miners had said they would stay off the job until they
received the full text of a government decree that officials say
fulfills promises made to get the miners to return to work last
month.
   After the earlier round of strikes, the government agreed to
bonuses for night work and miners using some dangerous equipment;
improvements in pensions and overtime; and made general pledges to
improve housing and end shortages of food and consumer goods.
   Tass said the miners struck again because they didn't have a
copy of the government decree.
   An instructor in the Organizational Department of the local
Communist Party headquarters said in a telephone interview that a
director of the state-run enterprise that operates all 13 mines
brought a copy of the decree from Moscow and explained it to the
workers.
   The miners then decided to return to work, Tass said.
   The Vorkuta miners struck July 19, several days after thousands
of miners in other parts of the Soviet Union already had walked out.
   They demanded improvements in living and working conditions, and
also that the government pay more attention to the problems of
workers in the country's far north.
   The returned to work five days later but said they would walk
out again if the government did not live up to its promises.
</TEXT>
