<DOCNO> AP890806-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PilotShortage     08-06 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilot Shortage,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boom In Pilot Hiring Puts Pressure On Civilian, Military Aviation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airlines are hiring record numbers of pilots,
raising concerns over safety and future shortages of men and women
to fly military and civilian planes.
   Large and small carriers have hired 12,000 pilots so far this
year, compared to 9,800 for all of last year, according to the Air
Line Pilots Association.
   But not all of the new hires are new pilots. Many are moving up
an informal ladder to flying the most sophisticated commercial
jets, resulting in an exodus among military pilots and turnover of
up to 120 percent a year for small carriers. Flight schools also
are seeing more trainers leave to enter the cockpit.
   The problem also has increased debate over the mandatory
retirement of commercial airline pilots at age 60, flight
experience requirements for pilots who fly passenger jets and the
loss of billions of dollars in training military pilots who quit to
join airlines that have no training programs of their own.
   ``The military and the regional airlines together continue to
supply a large share of the major airline pilot workforce, but they
cannot meet the present or future demand,'' said Henry A. Duffy,
president of the 41,000-member pilots union.
   Duffy and other aviation experts testified last week before the
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation subcommittee on
aviation, which is looking into the nation's pilot supply.
   Airline industry analysts estimate that between 40,000 and
60,000 new pilots will be needed over the next decade.
   Duffy said the military is losing 1,000 more pilots a year than
it trains.
   Karen Keesling, Air Force assistant secretary, said that if the
loss of trained military pilots is not stopped, the Air Force will
have a shortage of 2,800 pilots in five years and will lose several
billions of dollars in training.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., suggested that major airlines should
pay the cost of training military pilots who leave to fly passenger
planes. He also said the industry and the government should explore
the possibility of retaining older, experienced pilots who now have
to retire at 60.
   John S. Fredericksen of the Regional Airline Association said
that small carriers have to replace an average of 40 percent of
their pilots each year, with some having to replace all of them.
   ``All commuters enthusiastically seek out qualified pilots who
have no interest in a major airline career,'' he said, adding that
some companies are hiring pilots with relatively low total flying
time.
   Small carriers and charter airlines pay beginning flight crew
salaries as low as under $20,000 a year, while pilots for major
airlines can earn over $100,000.
   John D. Odegard, head of the University of North Dakota's
government-subsidized aerospace school which trains pilots, said
the need for pilots is ``staggering.''
   ``Massive pilot retirements, fewer ex-military pilots and
explosive industry growth _ growth which is expected to double to
one billion enplanements by the turn of the century'' are causing
the turnover and the threat of a pilot shortage, Odegard told
subcommittee.
   ``This turnover and its resulting decline in the relative
experience levels of pilots is beginning to raise serious questions
about maintaining air safety,'' Odegard said.
   He noted that young military pilots are put at the controls of
the world's most sophisticated jet aircraft after only 250 hours of
experience. Newly hired jetliner pilots averaged 1,500 hours last
year, but this was down from about 2,500 in 1981.
   Some aviation experts propose that performance levels rather
than flight experience should be the major factor in hiring.
   ``I believe a program of concentrated and professionally
structured training can be an effective substitute for in-flight
experience,'' said Kenneth L. Tallman, a retired Air Force general
who is president of the Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in
Florida.
   Tallman said enrollments in pilot training programs are
approaching record levels, but after training a young pilot ``is
cast into the great unknown.''
   He said there is no structured path for a pilot to follow to a
job as airliner pilot. One young pilot, following a typical path,
worked flying banners, hauled night freight, carried daily
newspapers, and flew a commuter service to accumulate enough hours
to be hired by a major airline, he said.
   The nation needs a civilian flight training program backed by
the Federal Aviation Administration, Tallman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
