<DOCNO> AP890806-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WatchingtheActivists Bjt   08-06 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Watching the Activists, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Business Pays to Find Out About Adversaries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a few eyebrows were raised at the
Natural Resources Defense Council when word filtered in that a book
detailing the activist environmental group's work was being peddled
for $1,500 a copy to big business.
   ``I find this a little odd,'' said Paul Allen, spokesman for the
council.
   A Washington consulting firm, Mongoven, Biscoe &amp; Duchin, mailed
solicitations to corporations last week offering a report on the
group, and promising information and analysis on its leaders,
issues and methods.
   Ronald A. Duchin, a veteran public relations executive who
formerly was a spokesman for the Pentagon, said all the information
is gleaned by his firm from public sources, such as newspapers,
annual reports and other publications.
   ``We don't monitor them because they're evil,'' he said. ``We
monitor them because our clients need information about what's on
their agenda.''
   Whatever the motivation, his firm is operating in a relatively
new and apparently growing area of research and management
consulting for corporate clients who want to know what
environmental or social activists are up to.
   The report was offered, Duchin's solicitation said, to
corporations that might be ``concerned with the NRDC's involvement
in environmental public policy issues.''
   Allen quickly learned of the report from friends who had been
offered the chance to buy it last week.
   He called the consulting firm to see what was going on. Duchin,
its senior vice president, brought over a free copy.
   The firm, established last year, offers what it describes as
``public policy intelligence'' on activists in environmental,
animal rights and consumer organizations, as well as citizens
groups, groups opposing biotechnology and even churches.
   ``MBD maintains extensive files on individuals and organizations
(all from public sources) and is able to provide timely information
and assessment of their activities and plans,'' the firm said in a
description Duchin mailed with the solicitation.
   Duchin said his firm is different from some others, however,
because it sticks to public sources of information and engages in
no spying, infiltration or corporate espionage.
   ``We monitor them. We make it our business to learn as much as
we can about them,'' Duchin said.
   The targets of their research generally would be described as
liberal, although Duchin said there was no intent to focus only on
the left.
   He said his firm has scrutinized national church organizations,
including the United Church of Christ and the United Methodist
Church, because of their support for animal rights' activists and
other activities.
   He said his clients include large chemical companies, but he
would not identify them. They pay monthly retainers of $3,500 to
$9,000 a month to be kept informed on certain issues and groups, he
said.
   The mailing on the NRDC went to 125 companies, he said. He
expects 20 or 25 to buy the one-time report and perhaps other
services. The report went free to regular clients.
   Allen says the Natural Resources Defense Council still is trying
to decide what to make of it, but ``there is something vaguely
sinister about it.''
   The report, he said, was generally flattering in describing the
group's effectiveness, although it misspelled the names of some
officials.
   He disagreed only on the report's conclusions that the group's
reputation had been damaged by the short-lived Alar scar, which was
triggered by the NRDC's report on the use of pesticides in apples.
   ``I guess I'm a little off put by the implication here that
there's something about us that needs to be revealed,'' Allen said.
``Do they have a right to do this? Sure, I suppose.''
   The council is a large environmentalist orgaization, more
establishment-minded than some other activist groups, and its
lawyers are engaged in litigation aimed at protecting the
environment.
   Allen said he saw no evidence there was anything other than
public sources used. Most of the information seemed to come from
the group's annual reports, he said.
   ``The price perplexes me more than anything else,'' Allen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
