<DOCNO> AP890806-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Switzerland-Drugs Bjt   08-06 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Switzerland-Drugs, Bjt,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Over Chocolate In Addicts' Park Highlights Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few steps from the imposing Zurich
national museum, where visitors browse through Switzerland's
history, passers-by are confronted with the country's most pressing
problem.
   Platzspitz park, once a favorite picnic spot, has become the
gathering point for drug addicts in this country, one of the
world's wealthiest, which has virtually no unemployment but one of
the highest drug addiction rates in the world.
   Most tourists, admiring Alpine views and shopping for watches or
chocolate, are unaware of the problem. And many Swiss failed for
years to grasp its size.
   But a recent killing in Platzspitz shocked the country. An
addict was tied up, gagged and drowned following an argument over a
piece of chocolate.
   ``What's wrong with Switzerland? Are we too well-off? Have our
young people really lost all sense of where they are going?'' said
Blick, the country's top-circulation tabloid.
   In 1988, there were 205 drug deaths in Switzerland. Figures for
the first half of this year suggest a sharp increase.
   Neighboring West Germany, with a population 10 times that of
Switzerland's 6.5 million, had only three times as many
drug-related deaths.
   In searching for solutions, an independent commission set up by
the Swiss government has recommended legalizing possession and
consumption of small amounts of drugs.
   ``Punishing addicts for harming their health does not achieve
anything. They need help,'' commission president Francois von der
Linde said in a recent interview.
   But he said suggestions to relax drug laws find little support
in other countries. The Swiss government has yet to reply to the
recommendations, but Arthur Grob of the Zurich police narcotics
department dismissed them as ``impossible and unworkable.''
   The Swiss Justice Ministry says most drugs smuggled into
Switzerland are heroin from Turkey and cocaine from South America.
   Dr. Werner Fuchs of the Zurich AIDS Intervention Project is
pessimistic.
   ``There is no solution to the drug problem,'' he told The
Associated Press. Instead, he said, officials should work on
containing the spread of the AIDS virus among Switzerland's 10,000
to 15,000 heroin addicts.
   Switzerland has the highest AIDS rate in Europe with 122.1 cases
per million people, ahead of France with 115.3, according to the
World Health Organization. Nearly a third of the 806 AIDS cases
reported in Switzerland by March were intravenous drug users. Half
of the 806 victims were homosexual or bisexual males.
   Fuchs works with doctors, nurses, social workers and volunteers
who operate 16 hours a day at Platzspitz. They provide needles,
free AIDS tests, meals, washing facilities and advice to those who
will listen.
   Zurich city councilors have authorized the free distribution of
syringes in the park to counter the spread of AIDS. Fuchs says when
the weather is fine, his team hands out as many as 5,000 new
syringes a day in exchange for used ones.
   Park benches are filled with young people. Some are asleep, some
stare vacantly into space, others inject heroin. No one bothers
about onlookers. A young girl wanders around eating a piece of
cake. Her face is covered with boils, her arms and legs are scarred
with the marks of drug abuse.
   Around a fountain at the park's center stand a few tables,
makeshift bases for the dealers. Nearby are two huge garbage
containers filled with empty soda cans, beer bottles and thousands
of syringe wrappers.
   Grob claims Platzspitz encourages addiction and acts as a magnet
to people because they know they can get food, syringes and medical
care.
   The square's population can reach 500 on weekends.
   Martin, a self-described volunteer who refused to give his last
name, is scornful of passers-by and tourists who regard the addicts
as freaks.
   ``The other day a busload of Japanese tourists stopped near the
park. They all got out and took photos of us, as if we were caged
zoo animals,'' he said.
   A barber by training, Martin offers haircuts and tints for $3
and entertains the crowd with an accordion.
   Though violence is not uncommon in the drug scene, even police
were shocked when the bound and gagged body of 23-year-old addict
Rolf von Arx was fished out of the river flowing by the park. His
two attackers admitted he was still alive when they tossed him into
the water after an argument over a bar of chocolate and a spilled
drink.
   Local magistrate Helene Wormser told journalists, ``Platzspitz
has seen fights and shootings but no one before has thought of
drowning a fellow human like a cat.''
</TEXT>
