<FIRST>r a AM-MidwestDrought Bjt   08-06 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midwest Drought, Bjt,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Farmers Still Sweating Out Drought, But Conditions Better Than
1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parts of the Midwest remain in the grip
of extreme drought, but timely rains have kept fields green in much
of the nation's grain belt even if little or none of the moisture
is being stored in the soil.
   ``This is our second year living from rain shower to rain
shower. Our whole family financial condition rests on the next
rain,'' said Mark Nagle, who raises corn and soybeans eight miles
southwest of Mason City in north central Iowa. ``You kind of wonder
how long it can go.''
   Extreme drought lingers in most of Iowa and North Dakota and in
parts of Illinois, Kansas, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska,
South Dakota and Wisconsin, according to the National Weather
Service. That's according to a weather service index that takes
into consideration soil conditions and long-term precipitation.
   ``The bullseye seems to be in Iowa,'' said Wayne Ellingson of
the weather service's Des Moines office.
   Drought disasters were declared this summer for North Dakota and
half the counties of South Dakota. In April, an emergency
proclamation was issued by Iowa's governor so the National Guard
could help haul water to communities in six southern counties.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the drought of 1988 has never
ended,'' said John Enz, North Dakota's state climatologist.
   Even if the heavier-than-normal rain predicted for the next 90
days over part of the grain belt actually falls, it will take 18
months to two years for groundwater to be replenished in the
central Plains, said Norton Strommen, a weather expert at the U.S.
Department of Agriculture in Washington.
   ``We've got a long way to go,'' said Strommen, chief
meteorologist at the USDA's World Agricultural Outlook Board.
   In Iowa, statewide average rainfall totaled just 13.65 inches in
the first seven months of the year. That was only 69 percent of the
normal 19.67 inches and made it the eighth driest
January-through-July period in records that go back 117 years.
   That was far better than the 9.74 inches of rain _ less than
half the norm _received during the first seven months of last year,
the driest on record. But it still created plenty of problems for
farmers.
   Phil Kruse, another Iowa farmer, said that up to last week, rain
had missed his farm and corn leaves were turning pale and curling
up to preserve moisture. ``We've had dry spells, but nothing like
this,'' said Kruse, who grows corn, soybeans, oats and hay and has
a dairy herd near Waucoma in northeast Iowa.
   Last year, drought reduced his corn yields to about a third of
normal and his soybean harvest to around half normal. He got by
with drought assistance, reserve hay and proceeds from hog
operations that have since been discontinued.
   But Friday night, 1{ inches of rain fell on the farm and by
Saturday, ``everything started looking greener,'' said Kruse's
wife, Rosemary.
   ``Boy, was that nice,'' she said. ``He looked at the rain gauge
a couple of times and had me look at it. He didn't believe it.''
   Even with the increased rain, only 1 percent of Iowa's subsoil _
its reserves for plant growth in dry periods _ is deemed to have
adequate moisture.
   Ohio and Indiana, where crops shriveled last summer, had so much
rain this spring that planting was delayed. As a result,
pollination now is running behind schedule, leaving those crops
vulnerable if hit by a blast of hot weather this month, said Larry
Van Mier of the USDA's Economic Research Service in Washington.
   But crops still are flourishing in most fields, even though soil
moisture reserves are low.
   Kansas is rebounding from a drought earlier this year that cut
the winter wheat crop to its smallest in 23 years. More than half
of Kansas corn and soybeans are rated in excellent condition this
summer and more than 60 percent of the subsoil has adequate
moisture.
   Van Mier said it appears that among the 17 states that account
for 94 percent of the nation's corn production, yields this year
will be far better than 1988, when they averaged about 82 bushels
an acre. With normal rains through fall harvest, yields should rise
above 118 bushels an acre but not quite to the 119.6-bushel level
of 1987, he said.
   Nagle, the Iowa farmer, knows first hand the importance of
getting rain at the right time.
   That's what salvaged a normal harvest for his farm in 1988, when
blistering heat and extreme drought fried crops in the field
throughout much of the Midwest.
   ``This year, with timely rains, we'll have another normal
harvest,'' he said. ``You dodge the bullet so often you think
you're immune.''
</TEXT>
