<FIRST>u w AM-DutyFree-Dixon Bjt   08-06 0897</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duty Free-Dixon, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Linked to Dixon's Wife Emerges as Big-League Lobbying Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that acquires lucrative franchises
for airport duty-free stores has become a big-league lobbying force
in Washington, trying to curry favor with House ethics committee
chairman Julian Dixon and others.
   Dixon's wife, Betty, has a stake in a high-yielding joint
venture with Duty Free Shoppers Group Ltd. to run the duty-free
shops at the Los Angeles International Airport.
   The Dixons acknowledge on financial disclosure reports that they
have made at least $150,000 in two years off an initial investment
of $15,000 or less.
   Extensive activity by lobbyists from Patton Boggs &amp; Blow, a law
firm hired by the San Francisco-based company, is outlined in
papers on file with the Justice Department's Office of Foreign
Agents Registration.
   Duty Free Shoppers is one of more than 100 clients represented
by Patton Boggs, a high-powered firm that bears the name of Tommy
Boggs, son of Rep. Lindy Boggs, D-La.
   Many of the firm's clients are giants in their fields: Sony
Corp. of America; May Department Stores; MCI Telecommunications, to
name a few.
   But the Duty Free Shoppers' account also kept the lobbyists
busy, and Boggs personally handled many of the contacts, according
to interviews and documents.
   The company paid Patton Boggs more than $1.4 million in the
four-year period through 1988, a fee viewed as substantial by other
Washington lobbyists. ``That's a nice-sized account,'' said Edward
Van Kloberg, a lobbyist with a number of foreign clients.
   The documents paint a picture of Patton Boggs' staff frequently
on the telephone or in meetings with legislators, their staffs and
executive branch officials from the Customs Service and the
departments of Transportation or Commerce, agencies that have roles
in regulating duty-free shops at airports.
   Besides Dixon, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee; House Ways and Means Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., Sens. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, and Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, are among the
scores of capital power players contacted on behalf of Duty Free
Shoppers, the reports show.
   ``They were pretty good lobbyists for anybody they had,'' former
Rep. Cecil Heftel, D-Hawaii, said of Patton Boggs.
   ``They knew how to deal with the facts but in a way that was
favorable to their client,'' said Heftel, who left office in 1986
to run unsuccessfully for governor in his home state.
   Although Heftel said he routinely declined social functions paid
for by lobbyists, others didn't.
   In 1985, for instance, the lobbyists charged Duty Free Shoppers
$1,480 for a dinner for Inouye, the documents show.
   Henry Giugni, Inouye's former administrative assistant and now
the Senate sergeant at arms, ``was the only other government
official who attended Sen. Inouye's dinner,'' the documents show.
   On another occasion, March 11, 1986, Ronald H. Brown, a lawyer
for Patton Boggs and now the chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, bought dinner for Dixon, D-Calif., and two other friends.
   Dixon, who says he never talked about Duty Free Shoppers with
Brown, recalled that there was a ``brief `struggle' concerning the
$187 bill after dinner. ``Ron insisted he treat and did so.''
   Brown said two other contacts he listed with Dixon on behalf of
Duty Free Shoppers were ``mostly social occasions ... three of the
occasions were dinners.''
   It was at one of those events _ a Feb. 26, 1986 party thrown by
Patton Boggs _ that Betty Dixon apparently learned about the Duty
Free Shoppers ``investment possibility,'' Dixon said.
   On the same day, Patton Boggs officials reported lobbying Reps.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., Don Young, R-Alaska, Daniel Akaka,
D-Hawaii, Heftel and Stevens for Duty Free Shoppers.
   Stuart Pape, one of the lawyers who handled Duty Free Shoppers'
business, said it ``wouldn't be uncommon to lobby'' a variety of
lawmakers ``if you judged that he would be important or
sympathetic, or, indeed, antagonistic.''
   Boggs did not return telephone calls to talk about the business.
   Patton Boggs dealt with ``legislation relating to duty-free
bonded warehouses, U.S. Pacific trust territory relationships, tax
and other revenue matters,'' according to legislative reports filed
with the House.
   Duty Free Shoppers, incorporated in Bermuda, is a worldwide
operation with concessions to operate shops at airports in
Honolulu; San Francisco;, Anchorage, Alaska; and Boston, Mass.,
among other places.
   It has sales of over $1 billion annually, mostly from selling
high-priced goods like perfume and brandname items such as Hermes
ties and Gucci shoes to international travelers.
   Besides hiring Patton Boggs, Duty Free Shoppers is a member of
the International Association of Airport Duty Free Stores, a trade
association with about 50 members.
   David H. Bernstein, the association's president, said the
industry grew up in the 1950s to serve travelers who can avoid
duties on items they purchase for consumption outside the United
States.
   The more than 125 duty free stores nationwide generate about $1
billion in revenues, with some of that money going to subsidize
airports.
   ``Duty free sales enterprises benefit the United States in a
number of ways,'' Akaka said in a statement. Not only do they pay
concession fees to airports, they ``induce foreign visitors to
increase their overall expenditures in the United States,'' the
congressman from Hawaii said.
   In 1986, Akaka introduced legislation that established
guidelines for duty-free stores, including where they can be
located. The measure was incorporated in the 1988 omnibus trade
bill.
</TEXT>
