<FIRST>r w AM-UrbanLeague     08-06 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Urban League,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Called Threat to Minority Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT - time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Urban League opened its annual
conference Sunday with a call for Congress and President Bush to
roll back recent Supreme Court decisions that it said were
anti-civil rights.
   League President John E. Jacob said that without action to
reverse the high court's rulings, women and minorities ``won't be
allowed to play catchup. They'll be stuck with the effects of past
discrimination.''
   ``The court we once looked to as the protector of minority
rights has itself become a threat to our rights,'' he said.
   Jacob, in a keynote address to the conference, cited recent
court rulings: against contracts set aside for minority businesses,
preventing women and minorities from challenging standing seniority
systems, limiting the use of statistics in proving patterns of
discrimination and putting greater burdens of proof on victims of
discrimination.
   ``We call on the president and the Congress to carefully review
the court's anti-civil rights decisions and to frame corrective
legislation,'' Jacob said.
   Jacob also announced two new Urban League programs to provide
more minority workers with jobs and to combat drugs in the
community.
   The National Workforce Development Program is designed to help
workers get the training and counseling they need to obtain jobs
and to help link them up with employers who are searching for
qualified people.
   ``We will be able to help corporate America include minorities
in all of its operations _ from the factory floor to the executive
suites,'' Jacob said.
   The league also said it plans to push for tougher laws against
drug offenses and for prison sites that keep offenders out of
communities. It said it will organize a nationwide ``Blacks Against
Drugs'' movement to mobilize people against drugs and keep children
drug-free.
</TEXT>
