<FIRST>r w AM-CivilRightsAmendment     08-06 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights Amendment,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Confrontation Helped Inspire Little-Noticed Amendment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-noticed effort to freeze housing
funds to communities guilty of police brutality was inspired partly
by complaints from anti-abortion demonstrators in Pittsburgh, says
the measure's sponsor.
   The freeze amendment by Rep. Robert Walker, R-Pa., was quietly
tacked on to a Department of Housing and Urban Development
appropriations bill July 20 by voice vote.
   The amendment would bar municipalities from spending Community
Development Block Grants if three or more of their police officers
were convicted of using unnecessary force against peaceful
demonstrators.
   Not only would the freeze require a conviction, it would be
triggered only if it was determined the officers acted ``on orders
of superiors.''
   In an interview Friday, Walker said the amendment was inspired
partly by a March 11 demonstration in which several protesters from
the anti-abortion group ``Operation Rescue'' claimed they were
brutalized by police and county jail guards.
   No charges have been filed, but the U.S. Civil Rights Commission
has said it will look into the incident.
   Walker said he hoped the amendment, which cannot become law
without Senate concurrence, will get the attention of Pittsburgh
officials.
   ``To suggest Pittsburgh was the only reason for this is to
misrepresent the situation,'' Walker said. ``No doubt it would
apply to Operation Rescue, and they were fully supportive of the
amendment. But the amendment speaks about civil rights
demonstrators in general, and is particularly aimed at a policy in
some communities of using pain as a way of handling nonviolent
demonstrations.''
   The only House member to argue against the amendment on the
floor was Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y., who said it was confusing and
would set a bad precedent.
   Green said he was concerned about what would happen if, for
example, ``someone comes up to the secretary of HUD as he is
entering the HUD building and says, `Psst, buddy, three police
officers in Altoona have been convicted under the circumstances of
the Walker amendment.'
   ``At that point, the secretary must withhold funds from Altoona,
and I think it is a dangerous amendment, a dangerous precedent,''
Green said.
   Pittsburgh officials have been lobbying against the amendment,
which they term ``ambiguous.''
   ``We can understand the desire of a member of Congress to insure
the right of any citizen to peacefully protest perceived
injustice,'' said a July 31 letter to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., from
Pittsburgh Mayor Sophie Masloff and Tom Foerster, chairman of the
Allegheny County commissioners.
   ``However, there are any number of remedies in both federal and
state agencies available to a citizen who feels that unnecessary
violence was used against him or her. It is unfair to burden
Pittsburgh or other cities and municipalities with the potential of
losing these vital federal funds.''
</TEXT>
