<FIRST>r a AM-StabbingAftermath Bjt   08-06 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stabbing Aftermath, Bjt,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shocked by Stabbing, State Weighs Tighter Security at Mental Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was like something in a horror movie
_ 9-year-old Jessica Short was visiting a street festival when she
was grabbed suddenly from behind and stabbed to death by an escaped
mental patient as her mother and dozens of others watched.
   A week later, the story still haunts Connecticut, kept on
newspapers' front pages by a second escape from the same hospital
and by troubling questions about security at the state's mental
institutions.
   Mental health officials, who at first protested that they were
running hospitals, not prisons, have now moved to tighten security
around the state's small population of criminally insane mental
patients.
   But the new security has done little to comfort residents and
officials in Middletown, who have lived for years in an uneasy
peace with Connecticut Valley Hospital, a 120-year-old brick
complex that houses many of the state's 172 criminally insane
patients.
   ``People who walk with their children on Main Street in
Middletown hold their children closer now because of the
incident,'' said Mayor Sebastian Garafalo.
   On July 28, David Peterson, a paranoid schizophrenic, walked
away from the hospital where he was confined last year after
attacking a neighbor. He stabbed Jessica to death, apparently
choosing her at random from among fairgoers on a crowded sidewalk.
   ``I absolutely blame the hospital,'' said Vincent Amato, a
Middletown merchant. ``Who else could you blame? They were charged
by society to take care of this man who had a problem. They
failed.''
   Some mental health workers worry the incident has bred what one
official called ``a kind of hysteria'' against thousands of
harmless mentally ill people.
   ``They are not a danger to anyone. But the public puts all of
them in the same category _ that they are to be feared,'' said Edna
Jacobs, president of the Connecticut Alliance for the Mentally Ill.
``The public doesn't understand the nature of mental illness.''
   She worried that backlash from the killing could slow or even
reverse the state's efforts to make mental health treatment more
humane.
   Peterson, 37, was sent to the state mental hospital system in
February 1988 by a Superior Court judge who found him not guilty by
reason of insanity in the non-fatal stabbing of a neighbor. He was
being treated under minimal security at Merrit Hall, a section of
Connecticut Valley Hospital where patients are given certain
privileges based on their competence and behavior.
   At about noon the day of the stabbing, Peterson got permission
to go to the hospital library, but instead left the unlocked
building and walked off the hospital grounds unnoticed, according
to police and hospital officials.
   He took a bus downtown, where he bought a hunting knife for
$36.95 and blended into a crowd of hundreds at the street fair.
   Just before 3 p.m., he grabbed Jessica in front of an F.W.
Woolworth store and began stabbing her in the face and chest. The
attack lasted less than a minute. The dark-haired girl was dead a
half-hour later.
   Peterson, who is charged with murder, is now being held in a
maximum-security section of the Middletown hospital.
   Peterson's relatives guessed he may have acted out of rage at
his doctors. Through years of treatment for mental illness, the
family said, he has distrusted doctors and feared the medication
they prescribed would give him cancer. They also said he should
have been watched more closely.
   ``My brother should have been locked up,'' said his sister,
Diane Maynard. ``They should lock him up and throw away the key.
Something always happens.''
   The victim's family, aside from a brief statement thanking
people for their compassion, hasn't commented publicly on the case.
   The decision to put Peterson into a relatively free section of
the hospital complex had been made by the state's Psychiatric
Security Review Board, a 5-year-old panel created to ensure that
decisions about criminally insane patients are not based on a
single doctor's recommendation.
   Since the attack, the Department of Mental Health has ordered
tighter security, including locked doors, at all wards where
criminally insane patients are treated. The system of privileges is
under scrutiny; sweeping regulatory or legislative changes are
expected.
   ``No system will ever be mistake-free,'' said Paul Gionfriddo, a
state representative from Middletown. ``When a mistake happens _
and we had a tragic one a week ago _ you try to create a system
that is one step better than the one you had before.''
   Garafalo, the Middletown mayor, has suggested that patients with
criminal histories be forced to wear electronic tracking bracelets.
   ``The statement has been made that (the mental hospital) is not
a prison, it's a hospital,'' Garafalo said. ``Well, for those who
are criminally committed, it should be a prison, with treatment.''
</TEXT>
