<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   08-06 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Rocket Fire Capsizes Boat Off Jounieh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian rocket fire on Sunday hit and
capsized a boat carrying passengers fleeing Lebanon's beleaguered
Christian enclave, and a 15-month-old Lebanese girl and her
2-year-old sister drowned.
   Three other people were killed and 18 wounded in overnight
shelling duels and clashes across Beirut's dividing Green Line, a
police spokesman said. By police count, 542 people have been killed
and 2,284 wounded since the latest round of fighting erupted March
8.
   The boat, ferrying passengers from the port of Jounieh to a
Cyprus-bound Hovercraft, capsized when a Syrian battery fired 40
rockets into the sea. Crew members from the Hovercraft lowered life
rafts and picked up six passengers, and another eight were rescued
by a fishing boat.
   ``We'd come under heavy fire ... I believe we were their
target,'' navigation officer Cesar Abi Aql said in Larnaca, Cyprus.
``We dropped the rafts and four of us went to the rescue. I saw the
baby girls but I had another passenger clinging to me ... When I
went back, they'd disappeared.''
   The sisters were identified as Maya Nabil Azar and her
2-year-old sister, Roba.
   The Hovercraft, the Norwegian-registered Santa Maria, makes a
daily run to Jounieh to pick up passengers from the Christian
enclave north of Beirut.
   It usually anchors 300 yards offshore to avoid Syrian shellfire,
and passengers come aboard from smaller craft.
   The Santa Maria arrived in Larnaca with 320 passengers, shipping
agent Tony Mansour said.
   Syrian gunners bombard the enclave's coastline daily to prevent
supplies of weapons and fuel from reaching the Christians.
   The latest round in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war broke out
when Lebanese Army commander Gen. Michel Aoun blockaded illegal
ports operated by Syrian-backed Moslem militias that deny the state
treasury $100 million a year.
   Syrian troops joined their militia allies in fighting Aoun's
mainly Christian troops and besieging the Christian enclave.
   A Beirut police spokesman said the Syrians started shelling
Saturday night as a ship with food neared the Christian port of
Byblos and a tanker approached nearby Amsheet.
   Aoun's gunners struck back at Syrian batteries. The duels later
dwindled into random bombardment, said the spokesman, who cannot be
named under standing rules.
   He said Syrian and Christian troops also staged hit-and-run
grenade attacks along the three-mile line dividing the capital as
their tanks blasted each others' positions.
   Sniper bullets whizzed through residential areas and the two
sides battled near the city port in downtown Beirut's destroyed
commercial district.
   Shells and rockets rained on Moslem and Christian sectors all
night, forcing remaining residents to huddle in basements,
corridors and on stairways.
   More than 1.3 million of the city's 1.5-million people have fled
to safer areas of Lebanon. Men return in the mornings to go to work
but drive back to join their families early in the afternoon.
   Police said the Syrian army on Saturday brought dozens of T-62
tanks and BM-21 multirocket launchers into west Beirut and hills
overlooking the capital.
   The reinforcements arrived amid rumors that Aoun's 20,000 troops
might storm west Beirut to seize Lebanon's central bank, where most
of the nation's hard currency and gold reserves are stored.
   Around 40,000 Syrian troops have been stationed in Lebanon since
1976 under a peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League. Aoun
charges the Syrians betrayed their mandate by siding with the
Moslems in their fight to share power with the traditionally
dominant Christians who are a minority in the country.
</TEXT>
