<HEAD>Newspaper Holds Contest For Pro-Govt Essays on Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 12th graf, `The media...' to correct verb tense. Pickup
13th, `Many Beijing...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under such titles as ``Blood Was Shed Here'' and
``Young Woman, I Grieve For You,'' Beijing residents have been
submitting pro-government accounts of the city's recent turmoil to
an essay contest.
   In ``Blood Was Shed Here,'' Xu Dingjiang wrote that he watched
soldiers ``with tears in their hearts and guns in their hands''
restrain themselves from firing on a crowd that torched their
vehicles.
   Niu Hui wrote about a neighbor who reported that soldiers turned
Tiananmen Square, the center of seven weeks of pro-democracy
protests, into a crematorium for protesters they killed.
   ``I think after she saw the television video and understood the
true situation, she was very embarrassed,'' Niu wrote.
   Niu, Xu and the other entrants, whose works began appearing in
the tabloid Beijing Evening News last week, are competing for
undisclosed prizes to be given in November.
   Eight other papers or television stations are helping sponsor
the contest.
   The only requirements are that the stories ``touch the soul''
and be true.
   What is true about the tumultuous events that led to the June
3-4 military crackdown remains a matter of controversy.
   All entries published so far stick closely to the official
version, which says soldiers acted with restraint and that only
about 300 people died, including dozens of soldiers.
   Western observers, including hundreds of journalists, said the
army fired wildly at crowds and buildings and that the death toll
may have been in the thousands.
   The contest reflects the voracious appetite of the official
media for commentaries, letters and essays on what it calls the
``quelling of the counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
   The media, apparently convinced that previous crackdowns on
dissent and liberal thought ended too quickly, are hanging on this
time despite a notable slackening of public interest.
   Many Beijing residents said they watched the first television
documentary on the protests several weeks ago, a four-part series.
But three more documentaries have been aired since, the latest
Sunday night, and many people chose not to watch them.
   ``I have better things to do,'' said one local shopkeeper.
   ``It's too exhausting, all this politics, the same thing all the
time,'' said a Chinese reporter.
   Some readers also are wondering about the real effects of
publishing so many reminiscences. Many columns criticizing ousted
party chief Zhao Ziyang, for example, have accused him of such
liberalism that he is becoming more popular to ordinary Chinese
than he ever was in office.
   ``It turns out Zhao was pretty good,'' one worker said after
attending a political study class at which Zhao was criticized.
   On Saturday, after Chinese authorities jammed incoming Voice of
America radio signals for weeks, the official Beijing Daily
splashed its reports all over its front page. The paper called it
an exhibit of the U.S. government-run station's ``false news
reports,'' but it did not censor out phrases such as ``the Chinese
People's Liberation Army's bloody massacre of protesters demanding
democracy.''
   ``It appears they are being criticized, but really their message
is getting across,'' said the Chinese reporter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
