<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Refugees     08-06 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Refugees,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of East Germans Seek Asylum Via West German Embassies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 East Germans have sought
refuge in this country's East bloc embassies in an effort to flee
to the West, news reports said Sunday.
   The West German news reports emerged at a time when Hungarian
authorities say they may take the once unthinkable step of granting
political asylum to some East Germans.
   Hungary and East Germany are communist allies. However,
reform-minded Hungarian leaders are preparing for nationwide
multiparty elections while East German officials have stuck to
hard-line policies.
   A flood of East Germans attempting to leave their homeland
through Hungary has aggravated tension between the countries. It
has also prompted a flurry of diplomatic exchanges between Bonn and
Budapest in an effort to resolve the problem.
   The West German Welt am Sonntag newspaper said more than 200
East Germans are living in the West German Embassy in Budapest. It
said Bonn had rented an additional building to house the refugees.
   Hungary is a popular vacation spot for East Germans.
   Other East Germans have sought refuge in Bonn's missions in East
Berlin and Prague, Czechoslovakia, according to the news reports.
They said about 80 East Germans were at the mission in East Berlin
and about 20 in Prague.
   East Germany's state-run news agency ADN told citizens Sunday
not to seek refuge in West German missions in an attempt to force
authorities to grant them exit visas. It did not say anything about
punishment for those who ignored the warning.
   During democratic reform, Hungary has dismantled nearly half of
a 160-mile barbed-wire barrier along its frontier with Austria.
   The move has given new hope to many East Germans who want to
emigrate to the West. The border between East Germany and West
Germany is heavily fortified and guarded by troops, attack dogs and
sophisticated electronic alarm systems.
   One Hungarian Interior Ministry official, Judith Toth, said last
week that Budapest was considering whether East Germans can be
granted political asylum in Hungary, thus allowing them to travel
legally to West Germany.
   However, Karoly Nagy, the head of the Interior Ministry's
refugee office, said Friday that East Germans would have to clearly
show they are victims of political persecution.
   He said most East Germans caught trying to cross the border into
Austria were not fleeing political persecution but simply seeking a
better life.
   Nagy said the problem should be worked out between East and West
Germany.
   He confirmed that the passports of East Germans stopped while
trying to make an illegal crossing into Austria are stamped by
Hungarian officials.
   Critics of the practice say it exposes East Germans to possible
prosecution when they return home.
   However, Nagy said the stamp does not indicate that the bearer
attempted to flee to the West but simply states he was ordered to
leave Hungary.
   The Bild am Sonntag newspaper quoted the country's Foreign
Ministry officials as saying they are trying to get the Hungarians
to drop the practice.
   ``With the mark of Cain in their passports, many East Germans
face severe reprisals,'' the newspaper quoted a Foreign Ministry
official as saying.
</TEXT>
