<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-06 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Kill 70 in Sri Lanka, 29 Dead in Other Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lankan military officials said
Sunday that Indian peacekeeping troops killed 70 people in weekend
offensives on ethnic Tamil rebels in northern areas.
   The officials said 29 other people, including a Buddhist monk,
died Friday and Saturday in Sinhalese radical violence elsewhere.
   An Indian Embassy official confirmed the military offensive but
said only three Tamil rebels were killed in two days.
   The Sri Lankan officials, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules, gave few details about either the fighting in
northern towns and jungles or the other deaths.
   However, residents in the northern town of Vavuniya said by
telephone that about 70 Tamils were killed in gunfire and shelling
from Indian forces.
   The residents, quoting travelers who arrived in their city, said
23 victims had been identified as civilians. The residents spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Indian official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said he had no reports of any civilian casualties.
   Residents in Jaffna, about 190 miles north of Colombo, said 40
homes and 23 shops were destroyed in the shelling. Other damage was
in Velvettiturai, 20 miles north of Jaffna, they said.
   The claims could not be independently confirmed. Movement in the
area is restricted by the Indian troops, who were sent to the
northeast two years ago to disarm Tamil rebels.
   The Indian troops were deployed under terms of an India-Sri
Lanka accord in July 29, 1987. The agreement was aimed at ending a
Tamil insurrection for an independent homeland.
   Sinhalese radicals bitterly oppose the Indian presence, which
rose to about 45,000 troops. In 1987, they launched a violent
anti-government campaign, killing at least 4,000 people.
   The Sinhalese extremists also say the government gave too many
concessions to the Tamils in the 1987 accord, which provided
limited autonomy in exchange for an arms surrender by Tamil
militias.
   The government has also been negotiating with India on a
withdrawal of Indian troops. Sri Lankan officials say they should
be pulled out quickly, but India says a rapid withdrawal could lead
to more violence.
   At least 11,000 people have been killed in the 6-year-old Tamil
separatist war.
   In the latest violence by the Sinhalese militants, the radicals
of the left-wing People's Liberation Front shot and killed the
chief priest of a Buddhist temple in Puttalam, 75 miles north of
Colombo, a government statement said. It did not say on which day
he was killed.
   The slaying of Pokunu Bandana Hemaloka followed Thursday's fatal
shooting of the chief priest of a Colombo temple.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. Many
Tamils say they suffer discrimination at the hands of the
Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population and control
the government.
</TEXT>
