<HEAD>Two Men Presumed Drowned During Rafting Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with one body found. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THEINSVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man drowned and a second was missing
and presumed dead after their raft went over a dam on a stretch of
the Milwaukee River that had been marked as dangerous, police said
Sunday.
   The two went over the dam Saturday evening and got in trouble in
the rapids below it, said acting Police Chief Dick Preston.
   Rescue crews searched unsuccessfully for the bodies about four
hours until the search was called off because of darkness. Sunday
morning, searchers found the body of Timothy Thompson, 27, of
Milwaukee about a half-mile downstream from the dam, authorities
said.
   Crews continued Sunday afternoon to search for the body of the
second victim, identified as a 31-year-old Mequon man. His name was
not immediately released.
   The stretch of the river where the accident occurred, just north
of Milwaukee, was marked as dangerous and the two men apparently
ignored the warning, Preston said.
