<FIRST>u w AM-AdvanceGuru 1stld-writethru a0665 08-06 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Advance Guru, 1st ld-writethru, a0665,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>He'd Go A Million Miles For The Perfect Image ... Or The Right Band</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to add dropped article ``a''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the plane carrying presidential aide
Steve Studdert tried to land on Africa's Serengeti plains, it first
had to buzz the landing area to ``chase off a couple hundred
wildebeests.''
   That accomplished, he recalled, none of the passengers dared
deplane until some feasting lions polished off the dinner they had
felled nearby.
   The episode en route to an energy meeting in Kenya was just one
of many on Studdert's 5 million-mile odyssey searching out the
perfect image for three presidents.
   He went by air, in everything from F-16 fighters to blimps; he
went by sea, in everything from submarines to tugboats; and he went
by land, in everything from fire trucks to ambulances.
   But after surveying the sights from the shipyards of Poland to
the wild creatures of the Serengeti, the White House advance guru
is hanging it up at the White House to point his trusty jeep
homeward to the sleepy town of Highland, Utah.
   Studdert _ formally the assistant to President Bush for special
activities and initiatives _ said he wants to leave government for
a more quiet life, and denies reports he is planning to run for
governor of Utah.
   It's just time, he said, to spend his time on things other than
boating down the Mississippi to plan a presidential tour of flood
devastation or riding the rails across Ohio on a campaign whistle
stop.
   But he is not shy about recalling his behind-the-scenes role in
shaping years of presidential level memories.
   ``What was wonderful for me, as I look at the most recent Europe
trip, I realize that 45 days before the president went there, I was
there,'' Studdert said in an interview. ``I stood in an empty
church in Leiden. I stood in an empty square in Gdansk. In my
mind's eye I saw what I hoped could be. What a wonderful feeling it
was to go with the president and see it happen.''
   What happened was 25,000 Poles packed into the square in Gdansk,
cheering an American president. What happened was several hundred
Dutch sitting quietly in a church to hear an American president
speak movingly on democratic ideals that had taken root in the
Netherlands before there was a United States of America.
   To make those and hundreds of other events ``happen'' involved a
morass of logistical details including dealing with foreign
governments and southern country sheriffs on motorcades, security,
crowd control, press arrangements and other aspects.
   White House Chief of Protocol Joseph Reed marvelled at how
Studdert and his team coordinate the trips that in effect entail
moving the entire White House.
   Reed called him ``Cecil B. de Studdert.''
   A former advance man for Presidents Ford and Reagan, Studdert
was tapped by presidential candidate Bush last year to work on
flag-waving imagery that would portray Bush as the candidate of
patriotism.
   After the election, he accompanied Bush to the White House to
come up with event scenarios, speech settings, props and travel
plans that showcase the president's policy goals. He has headed up
the logistics plans that have taken Bush to 12 countries and 24
states in his first six months in office.
   Given his estimate that he's traveled nearly 5 million miles
doing White House and campaign advance work, some things were bound
to go wrong.
   Once he paid some teen-agers $20 to use their pickup truck for a
parade for presidential candidate Gerald Ford. He didn't find out
until the parade was moving around a race track that the truck
belonged not to the youths, but to a man in the stands, who was
shocked to see his vehicle roll by filled with press photographers.
   ``We never saw the kids again,'' Studdert said.
   Another motorcade problem came on election night in 1980, when
Ronald Reagan wanted to go to his victory celebration early because
President Carter conceded early. There were no motorcade vehicles
to be seen outside Reagan's house.
   ``We stopped the first six cars coming along. One of the cars
was driven by one of the Gabor sisters. We just loaded up the press
corps and said let's go.''
   One of Studdert's most harrowing days also provided his most
poignant memory, one of those small things one never forgets.
   It was his first assignment during the Reagan presidency _
coordinating the return of the 52 American hostages from Iran whose
return on Inauguration Day 1981 was negotiated under President
Carter.
   At the last minute he was told to find a band for the hostages'
arrival at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington. He scouted
around and found a Navy band. The only requirement, he told the
leader, was that his musicians be able to play ``Tie a Yellow
Ribbon.''
   They learned it on the bus driving to the base.
   Studdert wanted a marching band, but this one was a concert band.
   ``Today, you're a marching band,'' he told them.
   ``I will never forget the trombone player marching along playing
`Tie a Yellow Ribbon' with tears running down his cheeks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
