<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-06 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Dampens Much of the Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms fell over much of the nation Sunday as
temperatures in the 90s snapped records up to 54 years old in North
Carolina and New Jersey.
   Rain fell in central New England, New York, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Kentucky, Tennessee, North Carolina, Alabama,
Mississippi, Nebraska, Kansas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Texas and
Colorado.
   Near Hopkinsville, Ky., thunderstorm-generated small hail
damaged trees and power lines. Thunderstorm gusts also caused
damage in Dundee, N.Y.
   The mercury hit 92 degrees in Cape Hatteras, N.C., 1 defree
higher than the old record for the date set in 1935. It was 96 in
Newark, N.J., where the old record of 95 was set in 1955.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Houghton Lake, Mich., to 107 degrees at Needles, Calif.
   The low for the Lower 48 states Sunday morning was 38 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Monday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from New England, to eastern New York, New Jersey,
eastern Pennsylvania, Maryland, Delaware, eastern West Virginia,
Virginia and eastern North Carolina, from the Florida Panhandle to
Louisiana, central and northern Texas and the Texas Panhandle, and
over the Great Lakes, the upper and middle Mississippi Valley and
the northern half of the Great Plains.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 90s from North Carolina
to Florida, the southern Gulf Coast states, Louisiana and the
central Rockies; the upper 50s in upper Michigan; the 60s and 70s
from northern New England to the upper and central Appalachians,
the Ohio Valley, the rest of southern Texas, southern New Mexico,
the Rockies, Nevada, and much of the lower two thirds of the
Pacific Coast; near 110 degrees in the desert Southwest and in the
80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
