<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Prisons     08-06 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Prisons,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Inmates on Hunger Strike in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said 15 leftist political
prisoners are in critical condition Sunday after 39 days on a
hunger strike, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
   It said the 15 inmates were sent to a hospital Sunday but were
returned to the infirmary of the high-security prison in western
Aydin province after they refused medical attention.
   Two hunger strikers already have died. Officials blamed
dehydration. Newspapers said the men were beaten to death.
   They are among 280 prisoners who started refusing food at
Eskisehir prison on June 28 to protest restrictions imposed after
prison authorities discovered several incomplete escape tunnels.
   Anatolia said hunger strikes have spread to other prisons and
nearly 1,800 inmates in six towns and cities were fasting Sunday in
solidarity with the Aydin inmates and to protest the two deaths.
   The Eskisehir prisoners were transfered Wednesday to Aydin, 300
miles west, so that workers could repair damage to the prison. That
is when two of the strikers died.
   Aydin prosecutor Nural Ucurum said a special ward for 40
prisoners was prepared at Aydin State Hospital, Anatolia reported.
   The leftist inmates are among thousands detained after a 1980
military takeover halted a wave of political terrorism that pitted
a dozen leftist groups against extreme rightists. About 5,000
people died in that violence.
   According to the independent Human Rights Association, 1,542
people detained on terrorism charges still are in prison awaiting
trial and 1,357 are serving sentences.
</TEXT>
