<SECOND>AM-People-Wu'er,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Student Leader Stands Up the Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese student leader Wu'er Kaixi spent part of
the weekend at the Kennedy family compound on Cape Cod, but didn't
make it to a scheduled breakfast meeting with Mayor Raymond Flynn
on Sunday.
   Wu'er, 21, played a key role in the student protests last spring
in Beijing and escaped China just prior to the June military
crackdown at Tiananmen Square. He reportedly may enroll at Harvard
University this fall.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., invited Wu'er and another
Chinese student to the family's Hyannis Port home for a clambake
and a little sailing Saturday with, among others, Rep. Joe Kennedy,
D-Mass., Rhode Island state Rep. Patrick Kennedy, Eunice Shriver
and Ethel Kennedy.
   ``They were down at the compound and we drove them back to
Boston,'' Kennedy spokesman Marc O'Connor said. He said the missed
visit with Flynn apparently resulted from a misunderstanding
between the mayor and the students' representatives.
   Flynn spokesman Michael Lynch said the mayor was not worried
about Wu'er's absence. ``It was simply a matter of miscommunication
or a conflict in scheduling,'' Lynch said.
   Calls to The China Project in Newton, an information
clearinghouse for Chinese students, went unanswered Sunday, but
O'Connor said he believed Wu'er was staying with students in the
area.
