<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1833EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hiroshima-Crew     08-06 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hiroshima-Crew,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Airmen Say Dropping the Bomb Saved Lives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hiroshima, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Two of the airmen who dropped the atomic bomb on Hiroshima in
the world's first nuclear attack 44 years ago Sunday say they still
have no regrets about the mission, and they insist it sped up the
end of the war with Japan.
   Jacob Beser, 68, was aboard the bomber Enola Gay, which dropped
the bomb on Hiroshima on Aug. 6, 1944, and Bock's Car, which bombed
Nagasaki three days later.
   ``A popular misconception is that we reacted like, `My God, what
did we do?''' said the retired engineer. ``Instead, just like every
other G.I. on a mission, it was, `My God, look at that ... go!'''
   About 140,000 people were killed in the Hiroshima attack and
70,000 died at Nagasaki. Japan surrendered unconditionally on Aug.
15, 1945, ending World War II without the costly invasion the
United States had feared it would have to mount.
   ``What we did was right, was necessary, saved lives _ and I hope
we never have to do it again,'' Beser said this weekend in Memphis.
``I have a lot of confidence in the future.''
   Retired Brig. Gen. Paul Tibbetts Jr., who flew the Enola Gay
over Hiroshima and into history, said that at the time he thought,
``if I am successful, I can bring this war to a quick end.''
   Tibbetts, 74, said he had no qualms about the mission, but has
occasionally been questioned by anti-nuclear groups or individuals.
   ``I don't have to justify it with anybody,'' he said recently
from his home in Columbus, Ohio.
   ``I did what I was supposed to do _ exactly what I was supposed
to do,'' Tibbetts said. ``I carried out a very successful bombing
mission. I didn't want to be a hero.''
   Then-Col. Tibbetts was one of America's most experienced bomber
pilots when he was given the top-secret Hiroshima mission.
   ``Being only 29 years old when I got the assignment ... there
wasn't anything that was going to stop me,'' he said.
   He and his crew of 14 took off in their B-29 Superfortress early
the morning of Aug. 6 from Tinian Island in the western Pacific,
1,750 miles from Hiroshima.
   The Enola Gay arrived at its destination at 8:15 a.m local time,
and dropped its deadly payload from 31,000 feet. It exploded in a
blinding flash.
   Then-Lt. Beser's job was to monitor Japan for possible
electronic interference that could cause the bombs to malfunction.
   ``I never saw the city of Hiroshima,'' he said. ``I just saw
this big, boiling mess, and fires breaking out on the periphery.''
   Beser, who visited Hiroshima in 1985, said he felt detached
during the bombing missions.
   ``If somebody had given me a rifle and said, `Go out and kill
those Japanese,' I'm not sure I could have done it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
