<FIRST>r a AM-BrokerageShootings     08-06 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brokerage Shootings,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widow of Man Who Shot Stockbrokers, Self Seeks Insurance Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of a man who killed a stockbroker,
wounded another and killed himself after losing a fortune in the
1987 stock market crash is battling his insurance companies in
court for $1.5 million in unpaid claims.
   Judith Kane, 49, claims she is entitled to collect $1 million
from Bankers Security Life Insurance and $500,000 from Prudential
Insurance Co. on life insurance policies taken out by her late
husband, Arthur Kane.
   But both insurers refuse to pay because Arthur Kane never told
them he was really Arthur Katz, a disbarred lawyer in the federal
witness protection program.
   Last week, a three-judge panel from the Atlanta-based 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals traveled to Miami to hear arguments in the
case, which the insurers appealed after losing a round in federal
court in Miami.
   ``Bankers Security thought they were insuring a mild-mannered,
longtime government employee,'' Alan Fine, a lawyer for Bankers
Security, said after the hearing. ``Instead they were insuring
someone very different.''
   Fine said the judges acknowledged the case is unique.
   ``There is no Florida law covering this kind of situation,'' he
said.
   But Mrs. Kane's lawyer, David Pollack, was upbeat about the
outcome of the appeal.
   ``We are confident she'll win again,'' Pollack said.
   A ruling was expected in six months, Fine said.
   The appeal is the latest round in the dispute that broke out
over Kane's life insurance policies shortly after his suicide.
   Kane, 53, reportedly lost $4 million in the Oct. 19, 1987,
crash. A week later, he walked into the Merrill Lynch office in
suburban Miami with a .357-caliber Magnum pistol and shot office
manager Jose Argilagos to death.
   He next turned the gun on his stockbroker, Lloyd Kolokoff, and
shot him in the back, paralyzing him for life. Kane then killed
himself.
   The two-year suicide exclusion clause in his insurance policies
had expired.
   The shootings put Kane in the national spotlight, and revealed
he really was Katz, a federal informant with suspected ties to
organized crime.
   Katz was a disbarred Kansas City, Mo., lawyer given a new
identity 11 years earlier after testifying for the government in
several cases.
   While Kane earned $29,676 working at the Social Security
Administration in Miami, he lived in a $430,000, six-bedroom home
in Miami's prosperous Kendall section.
   According to Bankers Security of Virginia and Prudential of New
Jersey, Kane negated his policies by not disclosing his real name.
</TEXT>
