<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0654 08-06 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Defy Restrictions At Cape Town Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with activists defying police restrictions;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one anti-apartheid
activists openly defied their police restrictions Sunday by
appearing at a rally where speakers called for intensifying a
nationwide civil disobedience campaign.
   On Sunday, an estimated 2,000 people, led by Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, attended an evening service at the African Methodist
Episcopal church in the mixed-race township of Athlone outside Cape
Town.
   Tutu and the Rev. Allan Boesak urged the crowd to support a
recently launched mass defiance campaign that is the most ambitious
such effort by opposition groups in 30 years.
   The 21 activists, who publicly identified themselves and said
they would not abide by their police orders, have been restricted
since their release from detention earlier this year.
   The restrictions vary, but most activists are required to be at
home from dusk to dawn and are not allowed to attend meetings where
the government is criticized.
   No uniformed police were present.
   The government has released almost 1,000 detainees since they
went on a hunger strike in January. However, about half have been
placed under restriction orders, according to human rights groups.
   An estimated 30,000 people, almost all black, have been detained
without charge for varying lengths of time under the 3-year-old
state of emergency, although only a few dozen currently are held.
   The defiance campaign began Wednesday, when 270 blacks and
Indians sought and received treatment at whites-only hospitals. The
Mass Democratic Movement, a loosely organized anti-apartheid
coalition that arranged the protest, promised additional acts of
defiance.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok has said the campaign is ``a
time bomb that could explode at any moment.''
   Also Sunday, police said in a report on unrest over the past 24
hours that six black men were killed in separate incidents near the
southeastern city of Pietermaritzburg. Black factional fighting in
the region has claimed 2,000 lives since 1986.
   Four men died when blacks set fire to a house in the Mpumalanga
township outside Pietermaritzburg, and two black men were shot
fatally in separate attacks in nearby townships, the report said.
   A seventh black man was shot to death in Kwathema, east of
Johannesburg, police said.
   Main combatants in the Pietermaritzburg violence are the United
Democratic Front, a banned anti-apartheid coalition, and Inkatha, a
Zulu group headed by Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
   Both groups oppose the apartheid policy of race discrimination,
but the United Democratic Front favors confrontational tactics such
as boycotts, sanctions, strikes and protests that Inkatha does not
endorse.
</TEXT>
