<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 1938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Trial     08-06 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Trial,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Of Moslem Fundamentalists Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>by NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of 54 Moslem fundamentalists,
including a blind preacher twice acquitted of charges linked to the
assassination of former President Anwar Sadat, opened Sunday amid
tight security.
   The 54 were arrested following an anti-government demonstration
allegedly led by the preacher, Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, on April 7
in southern Fayoum.
   He and 48 others are charged with illegal possession of weapons,
attempting to kill a police officer, and assault on individuals and
public property.
   The crimes are punishable by death.
   Three others were charged in connection with the bombing of a
theater in Fayoum, and two were charged with distributing leaflets
demanding Abdel-Rahman's release.
   Police rounded up 1,500 fundamentalists in a nationwide
crackdown following the Fayoum protest.
   ``The government has made up these charges because we exposed
its evil and corruption,'' Abdel-Rahman said Sunday of his new
charges. ``We must have patience and not budge even if we are
jailed.''
   The defendents chanted ``there is no God but Allah'' as they
were taken to the court grounds in prison vans. Rows of security
police lined the huge courtroom, a transformed trade-fair hall.
   Presiding Judge Kadry Samak adjourned the trial until Thursday
and ordered Abdel-Rahman, who reportedly is in poor health, be
taken to the prison hospital. It was not known how long the trial
would last.
   The defendents, mostly young men dressed in white robes, said
they had been on hunger strike since Wednesday to protest prison
conditions and demand the release of Abdel-Rahman.
   Defendents interrupted the five-hour session three times to
alert the judges that one of them had fainted.
   Abdel-Rahman was tried and acquitted in connection with Sadat's
Oct. 6, 1981 assassination by Moslem extremists. He was also
aquitted in a trial of 300 fundamentalists involved in a subsequent
coup attempt in the southern city of Assiut.
   The government had charged that Abdel-Rahman instigated the
president's murder by telling his followers Sadat had abandoned
Islam.
   Abdel-Rahman, a former theology professor, is one of Egypt's
best known dissidents. He leads the Moslem fundamentalist Jihad
group, which Egyptian courts blamed for Sadat's assassination.
   The group advocates the immediate implementation of Islamic law.
</TEXT>
