<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Labor     08-06 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Labor,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three-day Postal Strike Ends in Legnica, Other Strikes Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal workers ended a three-day strike in
the southern province of Legnica Sunday but scattered work
stoppages continued in other parts of the country, according to
various reports.
   State television said the situation in the transport industry
remained uncertain.
   Rail workers staged a one-hour strike Saturday in Silesia that
idled about 80 passenger and freight trains.
   The workers have threatened a general rail strike if their
demand for basic pay of $96 per month is not met. The pay now is
about $60 a month.
   A meeting between the official OPZZ trade union, the independent
Solidarity union and transport officials is to be held Monday to
discuss demands by bus and rail workers, the official PAP news
agency said.
   State television said the postal workers in Legnica signed an
agreement with management Sunday, but it gave no details.
   A strike at a tire factory in the city of Grudziaz in northern
Poland continued and PAP said the workers' pay demands exceeded the
factory's financial reserves.
   Also reported were strikes by health workers in the city of
Lowicz and by tram-car operators in Walbrzych.
   Strikes are becoming frequent as workers demand pay increases to
cope with inflation that is expected to exceed 120 percent this
year.
   Some strikes are supported by the official trade union, some by
Solidarity and others by both unions.
   Over the weekend, several Solidarity activists from Warsaw went
to the provinces to meet with strikers and explain the independent
union's policies in Parliament toward labor disputes.
   Solidarity leaders have said the union recognizes the reasons
for the strikes but time is needed for reforms to be put into place.
</TEXT>
