<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 2006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-US     08-06 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-US,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senior State Department Official Arrives In Khartoum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen
on Sunday began a visit to Sudan that will determine whether the
United States will give aid to the new military government.
   Cohen, the senior State Department official for African affairs,
told reporters his talks with Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir and
other Sudanese officials will cover the new government's plans for
ending a 6-year-old civil war and rebuilding the economy.
   Western sources said Cohen also will study el-Bashir's position
on allowing delivery of relief supplies to southerners suffering
from a war-induced famine. Both sides in the past have used food as
a weapon in the southern war.
   Cohen said the two days of talks will help the U.S. government
determine whether it should invoke a law that would freeze $108
million in aid because of the military's ouster of an elected
government.
   A 15-man junta overthrew Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's
government on June 30. The coup made the country subject to a U.S.
law that stipulates aid must be halted to a country where a
democratically elected government is removed in violation of the
nation's constitution.
   Fiji was the first country to fall under the law in 1986, and
aid was halted. Sudan is the second.
   Western sources say $22 million in development and economic aid
to Sudan has been frozen since January because the country has not
paid dues on U.S. government loans for more than a year.
   The Bush administration meanwhile has made it clear that it will
continue humanitarian aid to Sudan, which amounted to $100 million
in the past year.
   Sudan is one of the world's poorest nations, and its economy has
been destroyed by the $1 million-a-day war in the south, where
minority Christians and animists are fighting for more autonomy
from the dominant Moslems of the north.
   Cohen opened his African tour in Cairo last week and flew to
Khartoum from Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
