<FIRST>u i AM-Baker 1stLd-Writethru a0663 08-06 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Baker Heads Delegation To Mexico for Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Baker comments on trip to
Mexico. Pickup 2nd pvs, `About eight...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III
expressed hope Sunday that a new era in U.S.-Mexican relations is
at hand after years of cross-border acrimony.
   Baker and four other members of the U.S. Cabinet came to Mexico
City for talks with Mexican officials.
   Baker told reporters accompanying him that relations with Mexico
were once in the category of ``managing irritants'' and his goal is
to ``create common opportunities'' between the two countries.
   ``I don't think the Unites States has a relationship that is any
more important than the relations with Mexico.,'' he said.
   He arrived here in late afternoon. The other Cabinet members
came to Mexico in another plane.
   Officials in Mexico City saw the presence of such a high-level
delegation as a reflection of the significance the Bush
administration attaches to laying the groundwork for a more
productive relationship with Mexico.
   About eight hours of talks are planned Monday on an array of
issues, but the dominant subjects are expected to be drug
enforcement and Mexico's economic prospects following a debt
reduction agreement reached two weeks ago.
   The meetings are being held under the auspices of the
U.S.-Mexico Binational Commission, and a State Department list
shows 41 participants from nine agencies in the U.S. delegation.
The commission was established eight years ago and serves as a
forum for regular meetings of cabinet officials from both countries.
   Besides Baker, other U.S. officials include Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher, Environmental Protection Agency
Administrator William Reilly, U.S. Trade Reprssentative Carla Hills
and the director of the U.S. Information Agency, Bruce Gelb.
   Presidents Bush and Carlos Salinas de Gortari are both relative
newcomers to their respective posts and the change in
administration in both countries seems to have contributed to an
improvement in relations.
   Under President Reagan, relations were dominated by mutual
recriminations over differing views on the conflict in Central
America, an issue that has faded in recent months.
   American officials also have praised Salinas for his handling of
Mexico's economic policies and evidence that he is serious about
grappling with cross-border drug smuggling.
   Living standards in Mexico have dropped precipitously over the
years, partly because of the country's repayment obligations on its
$100 billion foreign debt.
   But on July 23, an agreement was reached between the Mexican
goverment and the commercial banks to which Mexico owes most of its
debt. The agreement is expected to give Mexico some financial
breathing room by reducing annual debt payments of $10 billion to
$12 billion by more than $2 billion.
   The agenda for Monday's talks includes financial cooperation,
narcotics, immigration, law enforcement, the environment, border
cooperation and fisheries, trade and investment and cultural
relations.
   Baker flew to Mexico City from Houston Sunday afternoon. He was
to have dinner with Mexican Foreign Secretary Fernando Solana. A
luncheon with Salinas is scheduled for Monday.
</TEXT>
