<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0708,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Barrage Greets Soviet Official in Afghan Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th pvs, ``The Soviet...'' to update with
Tass report. Pickup 8th pvs, ``It was...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight rockets pounded Kabul
Sunday as Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze arrived in
the capital for talks with government officials. Nine people were
reported killed.
   Thirty-five people were injured, mainly in residential areas,
the Bakhtar news agency said. Four hospitals reported at least 52
injured.
   Guerrillas in the mountains ringing this city of 2.25 million
people started firing in the early morning, four hours before
Shevardnadze arrived from Moscow.
   It was one of the most intense barrages since the last Soviet
troops left Afghanistan on Feb. 15, leaving the government alone to
fight U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas.
   On July 10, Kabul was hit by 65 rockets that killed more than 30
people.
   Shevardnadze was expected to report to the Afghan government on
recent talks with Secretary of State James A. Baker III, U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and Iranian President
Hashemi Rafsanjani on efforts to negotiate a political settlement
to Afghanistan's 10-year-old civil war.
   The Soviet minister held two meetings with President Najib,
Bakhtar reported.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, reported that Najib and
Shevardnadze discussed prospects of a political solution to the
conflict. It said the foreign minister also reaffirmed Soviet
economic and political support for Afghanistan.
   No further details on the talks were available.
   It was impossible for Shevardnadze to miss the almost continuous
explosions during the afternoon. The familiar boom of rockets sent
some Afghans rushing indoors, though others remained on the
streets, shopping, selling food, and trying to catch buses.
   No group claimed responsibility for Sunday's attack. But the
guerrillas have claimed responsibility for previous rocket attacks.
   The guerrillas say they aim at military targets and accuse the
government of rocketing civilian targets _ a charge the government
denies.
   On Sunday morning, several rockets struck the capital's
southwestern Darulaman area, where the Ministry of Defense is
located.
   More than 20 rockets exploded within a mile of the Continental
Hotel in northwest Kabul on Sunday afternoon. One landed in the
garden. Several struck a nearby hill, demolishing a house.
   A few landed near the British High Commission, which was
evacuated before the Soviet withdrawal.
   At least two struck near the main Kabul grain silo, where more
than 100 trucks were waiting to unload wheat.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani has accused
guerrillas of trying to destroy the silo, which contains 20,000
tons of grain, to starve the population.
   Kabul has been hit by almost daily rocket barrages since late
June. U.N. sources said 68 rockets hit the city in the last week,
not counting Sunday.
   Between June 25 and Aug. 1, the sources said, 281 residents were
killed and 745 injured in rocket attacks and a car bombing.
   Amani said published reports that an attempted coup has been
foiled and a number of generals arrested ``are baseless and have no
grounds.''
   He accused the United States and Pakistan, which help arm the
guerrillas, of fabricating the rumors to intensify what he called
its psychological warfare against the Afghan government.
   The Western campaign is aimed at whitewashing the guerrillas'
military failures and discord among its factions, Amani said.
   ``Except for the blind rocketing which is hitting the city,
there is nothing they can point to and be proud of,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
