<DOCNO> AP890806-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 2036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SovereigntyCommission     08-06 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sovereignty Commission,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Legislative Commission Spied on Black Party Members in
1960s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commission formed by the Mississippi
Legislature spied on members of a black political party during the
1960s in an effort to keep them out of office, according to a
former governor's personal papers.
   The 1956 Legislature formed the Sovereignty Commission to act as
the state's watchdog to preserve segregation. It was abolished in
1973 when then-Gov. Bill Waller vetoed its funding.
   The Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party operated from 1964
until 1968 to provide alternative black candidates to the regular
party of the white-controlled state government.
   The spies compiled rosters of the party's supporters, obtained
records of its meetings and wrote elaborate reports about its
candidates' strategies, according to commission documents contained
in the papers of former Gov. Paul B. Johnson Jr.
   By Nov. 2, 1966, the commission had a list of 31 civil rights
supporters and the groups to which they belonged, including the
Freedom Democratic Party, according to papers of Johnson, who was
governor from 1964 to 1968.
   The documents in Johnson's papers came to light for the first
time after they were made available to The Clarion-Ledger in
Jackson in a July 28 agreement with the attorney general. The
Johnson papers are at a library at the University of Southern
Mississippi in Hattiesburg. The newspaper has not said how it
reached the agreement with the attorney general.
   ``To have been treated as a political threat, I feel
complimented,'' Lawrence Guyot, one of the 31 named, said in an
interview from his Washington home last week. ``The Sovereignty
Commission was concerned about destroying things. They wanted to
maintain the fear. ... They could only maintain their fear by
depriving people of the vote.
   ``We knew the meetings were being taped and people were acting
as human tapes,'' Guyot said.
   Educators and historians say the commission's files could lead
to the rewriting of state history books.
   For one, more people have claimed they fought for civil rights
than actually did, said Leslie McLemore, dean of Jackson State
University's graduate school of political science.
   As more commission documents come to light, ``you get a fairly
true picture of the participation,'' McLemore said. ``On the other
hand, you get people who were on the other side, trying to tone
down their conservative nature.''
   Charles Sallis, a history professor at Millsaps College in
Jackson, said he expects the files will show ``the kind of fascist
tactics whites were willing to use to preserve segregation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890806-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 2056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HostagePoll     08-06 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Poll,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Majority Support Negotiations, Oppose Bombing to Free Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans believe the United States should
negotiate with terrorists to free the Middle East hostages and
should refrain from bombing terrorist hideouts in Lebanon,
according to a poll released Sunday.
   Of the 500 people surveyed in the Time Magazine-Cable News
Network poll, 58 percent support negotiations while 39 percent
oppose such talks.
   Asked whether they support bombing terrorist hideouts in Lebanon
if innocent people might be killed, 60 percent said no, and 33
percent said yes.
   Seventy-six percent oppose paying ransom for hostages, versus 19
percent who approve of the ransom idea.
   When asked about sending in commandos to rescue the hostages on
a mission that could endanger lives, 50 percent rejected the plan
and 40 percent supported it.
   The respondents were evenly divided on whether the United States
should bomb targets in Iran because of Iran's link to the Lebanese
kidnappers, with 45 percent supporting such an action and 45
percent opposing it.
   Forty-six percent approve of the way President Bush has been
handling the hostage crisis, while 32 percent disapprove.
   Asked if Israel was justified in kidnapping Sheik Abdul Karim
Obeid, only 25 percent said yes; 53 percent said the action went
too far.
   A fourth of those polled said they believe Israel is partly
responsible for the death of U.S. Marine Lieut. Colonel William
Higgins, but one-half of the respondents said Higgins' Arab captors
were solely to blame for his execution.
   Higgins was kidnapped last year while heading an observer team
with the United Nations peacekeeping force in Lebanon. His captors
claim they killed him last week in retaliation for Israel's
kidnapping of Sheik Obeid.
   The poll was conducted Aug. 3 by Yankelovich Clancy Shulman with
a sampling error estimated at plus or minus 4.5 percent.
</TEXT>
