<FIRST>r a AM-InfantMortality     08-06 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Mortality,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Fewer Low-Birth-Weight Infants Die, But Infection A Big Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More infants of low birth weight are dying from
infections than ever before, but the death rate among such babies
has dropped sharply, according to a federal researcher's study.
   A separate study conducted in Alabama concluded that
low-birth-weight babies living in rural sections of the state are
at greater risk of dying early than similar babies in cities.
   The number of low-birth-weight babies in the United States _
those born weighing 5{ pounds or less and often premature _ dropped
from 286,528 to 248,104 from 1969 to 1982, a 13 percent drop, said
the study by Dr. Janine Jason of the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta.
   Among whites, the mortality rate for such infants fell from 130
per 1,000 to 73 per 1,000 from 1969 to 1982, the latest year for
which figures are available. For blacks, the rate fell from 122 per
1,000 to 72.
   The study, which examined 25,000 deaths recorded during the
period, did not cite an overall death rate.
   Infectious diseases, which were associated with 4 percent of the
deaths in 1969, accounted for 10 percent by 1982, the study said.
   One reason is that low-birth-weight babies are surviving long
enough to contract infectious diseases, Jason said. She said some
parents may not understand the seriousness of an infectious disease
or have the money or transportation to bring the child to the
hospital.
   ``This is especially worrisome because infectious diseases are a
potentially preventable cause of death,'' Jason wrote in the study,
published in the August edition of Pediatrics, the journal of the
American Academy of Pediatrics, based in suburban Elk Grove Village.
   Most of the babies die of respiratory failure or other physical
problems that occur because of inadequate physical development,
according to the study.
   In the Alabama study, which was also published in Pediatrics,
researchers said they suspect living conditions and lack of access
to hospitals are responsible for the greater risk to
low-birth-weight babies living in rural areas.
   The study, conducted between 1980 and 1983, found 15,969
low-weight-births during the period, with 13.1 deaths per 1,000
births. The rate in racial terms was 10.82 deaths per 1,000 for
whites and 15.84 deaths per 1,000 for blacks.
   Overall, the death rate of rural low birth rate babies was 14
per 1,000 compared to 12.9 per 1,000 for urban babies.
   The 40 percent of Alabama's population that live in rural areas,
especially blacks, have housing that is ``substantially worse than
that in some Third World countries,'' said Dr. Christiane Hale of
the University of Alabama.
   Hale and another researcher found that many parts of rural
Alabama have no indoor plumbing or running water.
   ``If there's no refrigerator, there's no way to keep formula
chilled, which leads to infection,'' Hale said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
