<FIRST>u i AM-Cuba-Suicide     08-06 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Suicide,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Cuban Official Killed Self Because of Drug Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the financial section of Cuba's
Interior Ministry killed himself because of ``dejection and shame''
over a drug scandal involving the ministry, a Mexican news agency
said Sunday.
   But the report in Notimex, the official Mexican agency, did not
say how or when Col. Rafael Alvarez Cueto committed suicide.
   It attributed its dispatch to a report published Sunday in
Havana in the Cuban newspaper Rebel Youth.
   The report said Alvarez Cueto left two letters expressing
``confidence in the revolution and in President Fidel Castro'' and
``dejection and shame'' at the drug scandal that sent four high
officials to the firing squad and 10 to prison.
   They were convicted of helping smuggle tons of drugs into the
United States in collusion with Colombia's Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Two of those executed by firing squads on July 13 were Interior
Ministry officials. The two others shot were army officers
including a highly decorated general who had commanded Cuban troops
serving in Angola to help that country's Marxist government battle
rebels.
   The article in Rebel Youth indicated that Alvarez Cueto had not
been implicated in the scandal. It said Alvarez Cueto was allowed
to keep his job while Interior Minister Jose Abrantes Fernandez and
other ministry officials were removed from their posts.
   Abrantes Fernandez was not among the 14 people court-martialed
in the drug scandal but apparently was removed because of the
corruption that occurred in his ministry.
   The military court was told that the army and ministry officials
involved in the drug scandal put official resources at the disposal
of drug traffickers, who moved tons of Colombian cocaine and
Jamaican marijuana through the Caribbean into the United States.
   Castro's Communist government has called the scandal, the
biggest since Castro took power in 1959, a betrayal of the ideals
of the Cuban revolution and a cancer that will be excised from
Cuban society.
</TEXT>
