<DOCNO> AP890806-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 2212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ABA-Kennedy     08-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Kennedy,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Justice Assails Neglect of Federal Judiciary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy criticized
the ``assault by neglect'' on the federal judiciary in the wake of
Congress' rejection of pay hikes for federal judges.
   Although Kennedy did not specifically mention the rejection last
March of the 50 percent pay hike, he told the American Bar
Association convention on Saturday that federal judges had suffered
``a devestating blow.''
   ``This is assault by neglect and I am confident that if this
situation remains unremedied, the integrity, the independence and
the traditions of the American judiciary will be compromised in a
way that is not likely to be undone,'' Kennedy said.
   ``The federal judiciary cannot retain its integrity and its
independence and its strength unless it can draw on the highest
ranks of the practicing legal profession to serve as judges on this
bench at the height of their careers,'' he said.
   He said the Supreme Court was not included in his assessment
``because we are in a special situation.''
   U.S. District Court judges earn $89,500 annually, while federal
appeals court judges earn $95,000 a year. Those on the Supreme
Court earn $110,000 annually, with the chief justice earning an
extra $5,000.
   The rejected pay raise was part of a package that included
salary hikes for Congress and administration officials.
   Kennedy made his remarks during an ABA panel discussion on
alternative ways to resolve disputes. Also on the panel were
Supreme Court Justice Byron White and Hawaii Supreme Court Chief
Justice Herman Lum.
   White said the backlog of court cases makes it imperative to
find other ways of resolving disputes.
   In federal courts alone, about 269,000 cases, or about 470 for
each of the 575 district court judges, were filed in the year
ending June 30, 1988, he said.
   One alternative in civil cases is the use of ``summary jury
trials'' in which a six-member jury returns a non-binding, advisory
verdict to help each side evaluate its case and encourage a
settlement, White said.
   In Hawaii in the past three years, 2,000 personal injury cases
have been resolved through mandatory, non-binding arbitration, Lum
said.
   The judiciary's Center for Alternative Dispute Resolution has
helped settle or streamline almost 50 complicated, multi-party
cases, he said.
</TEXT>
