<FIRST>r a AM-FakeKidnap     08-06 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fake Kidnap,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buffalo Man Admits Kidnapping Was a Fake, Flees U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who had claimed he was the
kidnapped son of a Florida couple has fled the country, admitting
that he assumed the son's identity after the boy was killed while
trying to escape a baby-selling ring.
   In an interview published Sunday in The Buffalo News, David
Bonnabel, 25, admitted his story was a ``stretch of the truth,''
but said he was only trying to bring to justice a baby-selling ring
that killed young girls and his closest friend.
   Associates and law enforcement officials said Bonnabel, who
claimed he was abducted as a child and held captive for more than
10 years in the Louisiana bayou, is nothing more than a talented
con man who has fled the country.
   ``The whole thing had a purpose,'' Bonnabel said during a
telephone phone interview from a Latin American city. ``But
everything got out of hand.''
   The couple whose son Bonnabel pretended to be, Joseph and
Marjean Hagans of Tallahassee, said they believe he is a Mexican
national who used them as part of an elaborate scheme to prove he
was an American.
   And they still wonder what happened to their son Jonathan, who
was three when he disappeared from a Florida beach 21 years ago.
   Originally, Bonnabel claimed he was kidnapped at age 3 and kept
captive in a trailer in Louisiana. Now, he says he is a native of
Guadalajara, Mexico, of French descent, who entered the U.S.
illegally as a teenage dropout.
   He says he was confined against his will in Louisiana in 1981,
at which time he met a 15-year-old boy named Jonathan whom his
captor claimed was her son. Bonnabel says he soon realized Jonathan
had been kidnapped by the woman and was being sexually and
physically abused and kept out of school.
   After several months in the Louisiana trailer, Bonnabel claims
he realized that the woman was a midwife who delivered the babies
of pregnant girls and sold them on the black market. He also claims
he and Jonathan witnessed the murder of one girl.
   Eventually, he said, after Jonathan was killed in an escape
attempt, he claimed Jonathan's identity as his own.
   Bonnabel now claims that, while conducting an extensive search
for his own parents, he realized that telling a ``white lie''
substituting himself for Jonathan would attract more attention.
   ``Then the publicity got out of hand,'' he said. ``But I played
along from that moment on. It was the only resource I had to get
help.''
   The Haganses flew Bonnabel to Florida for a reunion before
realizing he wasn't their son.
   Mrs. Hagans said she believes Bonnabel was ``involved in
something bad. Whether or not my Jonathan was involved, I do not
know.'' Now, she said, ``I hope he (Bonnabel) doesn't come back.''
   Carol Boyette, a relative of the Hagans family and an activist
in missing-persons causes, said Bonnabel finally recanted his story
because of overwhelming evidence and the threat of a blood test.
</TEXT>
