<HEAD>Nintendo Sues Firm For Allegedly Copying Game Instruction Manuals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDMOND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nintendo of America Inc. has filed suit
against a large video rental chain for allegedly photocopying
Nintendo video game instruction manuals and providing them to
rental customers.
   Fort Lauderdale-based Blockbuster Entertainment Corp. was named
in a copyright injunction lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in
Newark, N.J., Nintendo announced Friday.
   The lawsuit is ``the first of those which Nintendo will commence
to stop this illegal practice,'' said Nintendo attorney Lynn
Hvalsoe in a company release.
   Blockbuster spokesman Wally Knief said Friday that company
attorneys had not reviewed the suit and it was too early for
comment.
   Blockbuster operates 821 video-rental outlets in 42 states,
Knief said.
   Instruction pamphlets are included with video game cartridge
packages. The suit contends that Blockbuster has photocopied these
pamphlets and distributed them to customers who rent the games.
   Nintendo of America is based in Redmond, Wash. and is a wholly
owned subsidiary of Japan-based Nintendo Co. Ltd.
