<SECOND>BC-Lexus,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Luxury Car Aims at Gap Between Americans, Europeans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota's new Lexus LS 400 luxury sedan may cause
people to think twice about buying more expensive European cars _
even Mercedes-Benz and BMW models _ an industry analyst says.
   ``There is a certain cachet to something made in the Black
Forest, but how much more is one willing to pay for that cachet?
Maybe there are fewer people willing to pay more,'' said Mary Ann
Sudol, an analyst for Fitch Investor Service in New York.
   Reporters got a look at the Lexus cars Friday at a racetrack in
California. They are scheduled for introduction in dealer showrooms
Sept. 1.
   The first 1,000 vehicles were shipped to dealers Wednesday, said
Dave Illingworth, Lexus' vice president and general manager.
   The LS 400 will have a base price of $35,000. Illingworth said
most American luxury cars fall in the $20,000 to $30,000 range,
while many European luxury cars cost more than $40,000.
   ``Our game plan is to be right between the two,'' he said.
   The Lexus LS 400 is Toyota's first V-8 four-door luxury sedan.
The car has 250 horsepower and a top speed of 150 mph.
   With options such as leather seats, compact-disc changers and
dealer-installed cellular phones, LS 400s are expected to cost
about $38,000, Illingworth said.
   That was the price announced earlier this week for Nissan Motor
Corp.'s V-8-powered Infiniti Q45 sedan, slated to appear in
showrooms Nov. 8. The Infiniti's price includes all options.
   The new Japanese contenders are bound to catch the eye of
habitual European luxury model purchasers, Sudol said.
   ``In style and features and power they seem to be saying, `Look
what elegance and appearance and value you can have for about half
the price,''' Sudol said.
   Lexus also will offer a 156-horsepower, V-6-powered four-door
sedan called the ES 250 with a base price of $21,050.
</TEXT>
