<FIRST>r f BC-FreuhaufDemise     08-06 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Freuhauf Demise,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fruehauf Corp. Changes Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fruehauf Corp. is no more, after changing
its name to K-H Corp. as part of the automotive parts
manufacturer's sale of its truck trailer and maritime businesses.
   The company completed the name change at the close of business
Friday, it said in a news release from its suburban Detroit
headquarters. The name change was required under terms of the July
14 sale of its subsidiaries.
   On May 5, Toronto-based Varity Corp. agreed to buy Fruehauf for
$436 million and 55.5 million shares of Varity stock.
   The name change won't affect that takeover, K-H said in a news
release. The takeover is expected to be completed by the end of
September, said Robert Siefert, K-H's president.
   In March, a division of Terex Corp. agreed to buy Freuhauf's
truck trailer and maritime manufacturing operations for about $233
million.
   K-H now principally serves as a holding company for Kelsey-Hayes
Co., a maker of aluminum and steel wheels, brake parts and other
car and truck components.
   K-H will trade on the New York Stock exchange under the ticker
symbol KH, the company said.
   Fruehauf encountered severe financial difficulties after a
leveraged buyout in 1986, to avoid a hostile takeover, left the
company heavily indebted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
